english:
  title: Spring Reverie
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How many months have passed without you?
    The dark moon has circled eight times round.
    To whom shall I speak of worldly matters?
    Still my old friend does not return.

    Warm mud welcomes the swallows newly come,
    Rough rain opens the small peach blossoms.
    In solitude I sing of spring's stirring,
    As the east wind pours from my wine cup.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The eight cycles of the moon may reference a specific period of separation or longing, emphasizing the passage of time through natural cycles.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of returning swallows and blooming peaches contrasts the speaker's isolation—nature renews while the poet waits alone.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image conflates the east wind with the pouring of wine, suggesting how nature itself becomes a companion to the solitary drinker.
